<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD BASKETBALL LEAGUE IS MAKING IT BIG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID WILLIAMS, MEMPHIS COMMERCIAL APPEAL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One of Steve Ehrhart's first acts as World Basketball League commissioner was 
to tell David Stern, his National Basketball Association counterpart, "We're in 
no way going to be competing with you." 
</P>
<P>
Neither do the two leagues see eye-to-eye on matters of height or manner of 
play. 
</P>
<P>
The Memphis-based WBL stresses speedy, high-scoring games and is limited to 
players who are 6-foot-5 or smaller -- a height restriction that would 
eliminate the majority of NBA players. 
</P>
<P>
The WBL, which begins its third season in May, is truly a "world" league. North 
American teams play touring international non-league teams (which aren't 
subject to the height restriction) in games that count in WBL standings. The 
WBL plans to feature European and Asian divisions within three years. 
</P>
<P>
In short, the WBL concept appears to be catching on. 
</P>
<P>
"The average size in the NBA is now 6-9 (just over 6-7, the NBA claims)," said 
Ehrhart, 42, former executive director of the defunct United States Football 
League. "So many of the (NBA) players -- especially backup players -- are just 
not excellent athletes. They're there because they are big and big only. The 
most entertaining players are usually under 6-5. Michael Jordan told me he's 
pretty close." 
</P>
<P>
The WBL players don't play in Jordan's air space, nor for his astronomical 
salary. The league's five returning franchises from last season are in 
Youngstown, Ohio; Worcester, Mass.; Calgary, Alberta, Canada; Springfield, 
Ill.; and Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
Memphis will have a team this season. Franchises also are expected in 
Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, Canada, and possibly in another American city. 
</P>
<P>
Top WBL players have included 6-4 Alfredrick Hughes of Loyola-Chicago, the 
fifth-leading scorer in NCAA history; 6-4 Perry McDonald, a two-year starter at 
Georgetown; and 6-4 Carlos Clark, a former Ole Miss star and member of the 1984 
NBA champion Boston Celtics. 
</P>
<P>
The average salary is $15,000, and each team has a $150,000 annual salary cap. 
A team's typical annual budget is $750,000. By contrast, New York Knicks center 
Patrick Ewing last year earned an NBA-best salary of $3.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
The WBL's lower salaries translate to lower ticket prices. League attendance 
averaged 2,700 in 1988 and 2,900 last season. 
</P>
<P>
Only the Youngstown Pride, last year's league champs, have shown a 
single-season profit. 
</P>
<P>
"It takes some time because of the newness of the product," Ehrhart said. 
"We're still in the process of fighting for name recognition. There are people 
who haven't even heard of us." 
</P>
<P>
But by selling short, the WBL is able to make a strong pitch. 
</P>
<P>
For example: 
</P>
<P>
 -- Close, fast-moving games. The average score is 111-107, Ehrhart said. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Players don't foul out. Beginning with a player's seventh foul, the 
opposition gets a foul shot or shots and possession. 
</P>
<P>
 -- In overtime, the first team to seven points wins. 
</P>
<P>
 -- The WBL uses the international three-point line of 20-feet, 6-inches. The 
NBA's line ranges from 22 feet on the baseline to 23-9 at the top of the key. 
</P>
<P>
 -- A player fouled on a three-point try receives three free throws. 
</P>
<P>
The WBL also is entering the second year of a three-year television deal worth 
nearly $2 million with cable network SportsChannel America. 
</P>
<P>
Officials think the NBA and WBL can coexist. They also believe that WBL owners 
may one day have the chance to own NBA teams. 
</P>
<P>
"This gives us the opportunity to prove ourselves with this team," Memphis 
interim general manager Pat Carter said. "Hopefully, we'd be in line, in 
consideration for an NBA team." 
</P>
<P>
The WBL seems to be doing legwork for the NBA on matters of expansion, in the 
United States and around the world. 
</P>
<P>
"No question," Ehrhart said. "They're watching us." 
</P>
<P>
But NBA Vice President for Public Relations Bryan McIntyre said the league 
isn't watching the WBL's international expansion plans. He called the NBA, 
whose teams have played overseas exhibitions, "the top professional league for 
basketball in the world." 
</P>
<P>
A group including investors and promoters contacted Ehrhart in late 1987 about 
becoming commissioner. When he took the job in early '88, Ehrhart virtually was 
in a league by himself. 
</P>
<P>
"No players had been signed," he said. "They were debating whether to make the 
height 6-4 or 6-5. There was no name for the league." 
</P>
<P>
And the league was to begin play in May. "That was just a total all-out sprint 
to get stadiums, dates, players signed, rules adopted and published -- to tell 
people who we are and what we are, battle for recognition," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012190-0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 165133 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 21, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 11; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
308 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEPPERDINE COMES BACK AND BEATS GONZAGA, 68-67 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RAY RIPTON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With Gonzaga holding a 56-41 lead over Pepperdine with 8:34 to play, it looked 
as if it was going to be an easy victory for the Bulldogs Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
But the Waves picked themselves up and somehow beat Gonzaga, 68-67, before 
2,317 at Firestone Fieldhouse in Malibu. 
</P>
<P>
Shann Ferch's layup with 11 seconds remaining provided the decisive points for 
Pepperdine, which improved to 8-9 overall and 2-2 in the West Coast Conference. 
Gonzaga fell to 6-11 and 1-3. 
</P>
<P>
"After the year we've had, I figured we had to have a win like this," 
Pepperdine Coach Tom Asbury said. "We've had to many (go) in the other 
direction." 
</P>
<P>
"We've been letting people come in and play, and we have to get our backs to 
the wall," Asbury said. "We've done that so many times this year and quit. 
Tonight we didn't." 
</P>
<P>
Dexter Howard made one of two free throws to signal the start of a 13-0 run, 
and Pepperdine was on track, pulling within 56-54 with 5:08 to play. 
</P>
<P>
There were two consecutive three-point baskets, one by Rick Welch and the other 
by Doug Christie. 
</P>
<P>
Then Christie stole the ball near the Gonzaga basket and drove for a dunk. Not 
to be outdone, Welch also made a backcourt steal and scored on a layup. 
</P>
<P>
But Pepperdine, which trailed at halftime, 40-31, didn't take a second-half 
lead until there was 1:31 remaining. That's when Craig Davis hit a 
three-pointer that made it 63-61. 
</P>
<P>
A three-point play by Geoff Lear, who made some key rebounds down the stretch, 
extended the lead. 
</P>
<P>
Jim McPhee, who scored a game-high 23 points, followed with a three-pointer, 
but Ferch made it 68-64 for Pepperdine with his layup with 11 seconds 
remaining. 
</P>
<P>
Gonzaga's Darryl May made a three-pointer as time ran out. 
</P>
<P>
Christie scored 19 points on eight-of-14 shooting, Lear had 16 points and 10 
rebounds, and Ferch, who made three of three three-point shots, had 11 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
