<TEXT>
<P>
East Germany in 1976 narrowly averted a nuclear catastrophe on the scale of the 
Chernobyl disaster in the Soviet Union, the West German magazine Der Spiegel 
reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
According to the magazine, a fire at the Lubmin nuclear power station, near 
Greifswald on the Baltic coast, almost led to a meltdown of the plant's 
radioactive core when safety measures failed. 
